$x=\pi$ is indeed in the domain of $\tan(x)$:

$\begin{align}
\tan(\pi)&=\dfrac{\sin(\pi)}{\cos(\pi)}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{0}{-1}
\\\\
&=0
\end{align}$

$x=\dfrac{\pi}{6}$ is indeed in the domain of $\cot(x)$:

$\begin{align}
\cot\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)&=\dfrac{\cos\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)}{\sin\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{\left(\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \right)}{\left( \dfrac{1}{2} \right)}
\\\\
&=\sqrt{3}
\end{align}$

$x=\dfrac{\pi}{3}$ is indeed in the domain of $\sec(x)$:

$\begin{align}
\sec\left(\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right)&=\dfrac{1}{\cos\left(\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right)}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{\left( \dfrac{1}{2} \right)}
\\\\
&=2
\end{align}$

$x=\dfrac{\pi}{4}$ is indeed in the domain of $\csc(x)$:

$\begin{align}
\csc\left(\dfrac{\pi}{4}\right)&=\dfrac{1}{\sin\left(\dfrac{\pi}{4}\right)}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{\left( \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \right)}
\\\\
&=\sqrt{2}
\end{align}$

$x=0$ is indeed in the domain of $\tan(x)$:

$\begin{align}
\tan\left(0\right)&=\dfrac{\sin\left(0\right)}{\cos\left(0\right)}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{0}{1}
\\\\
&=0
\end{align}$

$x=\dfrac{\pi}{4}$ is indeed in the domain of $\cot(x)$:

$\begin{align}
\cot\left(\dfrac{\pi}{4}\right)&=\dfrac{\cos\left(\dfrac{\pi}{4}\right)}{\sin\left(\dfrac{\pi}{4}\right)}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{\left( \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)}{\left( \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)}
\\\\
&=1
\end{align}$

$x=\pi$ is *not* in the domain of $\cot(x)$:

$\begin{align}
\cot(\pi)&=\dfrac{\cos(\pi)}{\sin(\pi)}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{-1}{0}
\end{align}$

